boyd@math.ubc.ca (David Boyd) writes:
> In article <342u6c$ns5@news.umbc.edu> olson@umbc.edu (Bryan G. Olson; CMSC (G)) writes:
> >
> >Yes, it would work; x^(d*e) mod n = x even if x is not relatively
> >prime to n, although finding such an x is at least as hard as
> >breaking RSA.  ( I've been told the first version of the
> >RSA paper did not consider this case. )
> >
>   [Alleged proof follows]
>   
>     Try taking  x = 3, n = 3*5 = 15, so  phi(n) = 2*4 = 8.
>   
>     Compute  3^8 mod 15 = 6,  not  3  as claimed.
>   
>   
>                                     David Boyd
>                   
>                                     boyd@math.ubc.ca
